title: EBNF - Transclusion and Macros

This tiddler documents the EBNF grammar for transclusion, filtered transclusion, macro calls, and multi-valued variable (MVV) display syntax, as derived from the parser source code.

!! Transclusion

Both block and inline forms exist. The block form requires the `{{...}}` to be on its own line (followed by a newline or end of input). The inline form appears within text runs.

Five patterns are supported:

# ''Basic transclusion'' -- `{{tiddler-title}}` includes another tiddler's content
# ''Field transclusion'' -- `{{tiddler!!field}}` includes a specific field value
# ''Index transclusion'' -- `{{tiddler##index}}` includes a data tiddler index
# ''Template transclusion'' -- `{{tiddler||template}}` renders the tiddler through a template
# ''Parameterised transclusion'' -- `{{tiddler||template|param1|param2}}` renders through a template, passing positional parameters

The underlying regex from `transcludeblock.js` / `transcludeinline.js` is:

```
/\{\{([^\{\}\|]*)(?:\|\|([^\|\{\}]+))?(?:\|([^\{\}]+))?\}\}/
```

EBNF:

```
Transclusion     ::= '{{' TranscludeSpec '}}'
TranscludeSpec   ::= TiddlerRef? ('||' TemplateRef)? ('|' ParamValue)*
TiddlerRef       ::= Title ('!!' Field | '##' Index)?
Title            ::= [^{}|]*
TemplateRef      ::= [^|{}]+
ParamValue       ::= [^{}]+           /* split on '|' at parse time */
```

Note: the tiddler reference is parsed by `$tw.utils.parseTextReference()`, which splits on `!!` for field access and `##` for index access. Parameters are split on `|` and assigned positional names `"0"`, `"1"`, etc.

!! Filtered Transclusion

Filtered transclusion uses triple braces and produces a `<$list>` widget. Both block and inline forms exist, with the same block-vs-inline rule (must be alone on a line for block mode).

Four patterns are supported:

# ''Basic'' -- `{{{[filter]}}}` transclude all filter results
# ''With tooltip'' -- `{{{[filter]|tooltip}}}` adds a tooltip
# ''With template'' -- `{{{[filter]||template}}}` renders each result through a template
# ''With style/classes'' -- `{{{[filter]}}width:40;height:50;}.class1.class2` adds inline styles and CSS classes

All four can be combined: `{{{[filter]|tooltip||template}}styles}.classes`

The underlying regex from `filteredtranscludeblock.js` / `filteredtranscludeinline.js` is:

```
/\{\{\{([^\|]+?)(?:\|([^\|\{\}]+))?(?:\|\|([^\|\{\}]+))?\}\}([^\}]*)\}(?:\.(\S+))?/
```

EBNF:

```
FilteredTransclusion ::= '{{{' FilterExpr '}}}' StyleSuffix?
                       | '{{{' FilterExpr '|' Tooltip '}}}' StyleSuffix?
                       | '{{{' FilterExpr '||' TemplateRef '}}}' StyleSuffix?
                       | '{{{' FilterExpr '|' Tooltip '||' TemplateRef '}}}' StyleSuffix?
FilterExpr           ::= [^|]+?          /* non-greedy, no pipe chars */
Tooltip              ::= [^|{}]+
TemplateRef          ::= [^|{}]+
StyleSuffix          ::= StyleDefs? ('.' ClassName)*
StyleDefs            ::= [^}]*           /* between last }} and } */
ClassName            ::= \S+
```

Note: the style portion sits between the closing `}}` and the final `}`. Classes are dot-separated after the closing `}`. The regex captures groups are: (1) filter, (2) tooltip, (3) template, (4) style string, (5) dot-separated classes.

!! Macro Calls

Both block and inline forms use `<<macroname ...>>`. The block form requires the `<<...>>` to be alone on its own line. Macro calls are parsed by `$tw.utils.parseMacroInvocationAsTransclusion()` in `parseutils.js`, which produces a `transclude` widget node with a `$variable` attribute.

Patterns:

# ''Basic'' -- `<<macroname>>` calls a macro with no parameters
# ''With positional params'' -- `<<macroname param1 "param 2">>` passes unnamed parameters
# ''With named params'' -- `<<macroname name:value>>` passes named parameters
# ''Mixed'' -- `<<macroname positional name:value>>` positional and named can be mixed

Five quoting styles are supported for parameter values:

* Unquoted -- `value` (no spaces, no `>>`)
* Double-quoted -- `"value with spaces"`
* Single-quoted -- `'value with spaces'`
* Bracket-quoted -- `[[value with spaces]]`
* Triple-double-quoted -- `"""value with any content"""`

The parameter regex from `parseMacroParameter()` in `parseutils.js` is:

```
/(?:([A-Za-z0-9\-_]+)\s*:)?(?:\s*(?:"""([\s\S]*?)"""|"([^"]*)"|'([^']*)'|\[\[((?:[^\]]|\](?!\]))*)?\]\]|((?:(?:>(?!>))|[^\s>"'])+)))/
```

EBNF:

```
MacroCall        ::= '<<' MacroName (SP MacroParam)* SP? '>>'
MacroName        ::= [^\s>"'=:]+
MacroParam       ::= (ParamName ':')? ParamValue
ParamName        ::= [A-Za-z0-9_-]+
ParamValue       ::= TripleQuoted | DoubleQuoted | SingleQuoted | BracketQuoted | Unquoted
TripleQuoted     ::= '"""' .* '"""'
DoubleQuoted     ::= '"' [^"]* '"'
SingleQuoted     ::= "'" [^']* "'"
BracketQuoted    ::= '[[' ( [^\]] | ']'(?!']') )* ']]'
Unquoted         ::= ( '>'^('>') | [^\s>"'] )+
SP               ::= [ \t]+
```

Note: when the `=` separator is used (new-style), additional value types are supported: filtered values `{{{filter}}}`, indirect values `{{textRef}}`, and substituted values using backticks. These extended forms are available through `parseMacroParameterAsAttribute()` which is the function used by `parseMacroInvocationAsTransclusion()`.

!! Macro Definitions (pragma)

Macro definitions use the `\define` pragma (deprecated; prefer `\procedure`):

```
\define macroname(param1, param2:defaultvalue)
multiline body with $param1$ substitution markers
\end macroname
```

Or single-line form:

```
\define macroname(param1) single line body
```

The regex from `macrodef.js` is:

```
/\\define\s+([^(\s]+)\(\s*([^)]*)\)(\s*\r?\n)?/
```

EBNF:

```
MacroDef         ::= '\define' SP MacroName '(' ParamList? ')' ( SP? EOL Body '\end' MacroName?
                                                                | SP SingleLineBody EOL )
ParamList        ::= ParamDecl (',' ParamDecl)*
ParamDecl        ::= ParamName (':' DefaultValue)?
DefaultValue     ::= TripleQuoted | DoubleQuoted | SingleQuoted | BracketQuoted | UnquotedDefault
UnquotedDefault  ::= [^"'\s]+
Body             ::= .*                /* terminated by \end */
SingleLineBody   ::= [^\n]*
```

!! MVV Display (inline only)

The multi-valued variable display syntax provides a concise way to display variable values or filter results inline. Unlike the other constructs documented here, MVV display is //inline only// -- there is no block form.

Four patterns are supported:

# ''Variable display'' -- `((varname))` displays the variable's value
# ''Variable with separator'' -- `((varname||separator))` joins multiple values with a custom separator
# ''Filter display'' -- `(((filter-expression)))` displays filter results
# ''Filter with separator'' -- `(((filter-expression||separator)))` joins filter results with a custom separator

The default separator is `", "` (comma followed by space).

The regexes from `mvvdisplayinline.js` are:

* Variable mode: `/^\(\(([^()|]+?)(?:\|\|([^)]*))\)\)/`
* Filter mode: `/^\(\(\(([\s\S]+?)\)\)\)/` with inner `||` splitting for the separator

EBNF:

```
MVVDisplay       ::= MVVVariable | MVVFilter
MVVVariable      ::= '((' VarName ('||' Separator)? '))'
MVVFilter        ::= '(((' FilterExpr ('||' Separator)? ')))'
VarName          ::= [^()|]+?          /* non-greedy */
Separator        ::= [^)]*             /* defaults to ", " if omitted */
FilterExpr       ::= [\s\S]+?          /* non-greedy, terminated by ))) */
```

At runtime, variable display is compiled to the filter `[(<varname>)join[<sep>]]` and filter display appends `+[join[<sep>]]` to the user's filter. The result is rendered via a `<$text>` widget with a filtered `text` attribute.

!! Block vs Inline Distinction

Transclusion, filtered transclusion, and macro calls all have ''both'' block and inline parser rules. The distinction matters for how the output is rendered:

* ''Block form'' -- The construct must appear alone on its own line: nothing before `{{`, `{{{`, or `<<` on that line, and immediately followed by a newline or end of input. Block-level nodes set `isBlock: true` on the parse tree node, which causes the widget to render in block mode (producing `<div>` wrappers rather than `<span>`).

* ''Inline form'' -- The construct appears within a run of inline text. No `isBlock` flag is set, and the output is rendered inline (within `<span>` or `<p>` elements).

The block regex variants append `(?:\r?\n|$)` to enforce the end-of-line requirement. The inline variants omit this.

MVV display `((...))` is the exception: it exists only as an inline rule. There is no block-level variant.

!! Combined EBNF

```
(* === Transclusion === *)
Transclusion       ::= '{{' TranscludeSpec '}}'
TranscludeSpec     ::= TiddlerRef? ('||' TemplateRef)? ('|' ParamValue)*
TiddlerRef         ::= Title ('!!' Field | '##' Index)?
Title              ::= [^{}|]*
TemplateRef        ::= [^|{}]+

(* === Filtered Transclusion === *)
FilteredTransclusion ::= '{{{' FilterExpr Tooltip? Template? '}}}' StyleSuffix?
Tooltip              ::= '|' [^|{}]+
Template             ::= '||' [^|{}]+
StyleSuffix          ::= StyleDefs? ('.' ClassName)*
StyleDefs            ::= [^}]*
ClassName            ::= \S+

(* === Macro Call === *)
MacroCall          ::= '<<' MacroName (SP MacroParam)* SP? '>>'
MacroName          ::= [^\s>"'=:]+
MacroParam         ::= (ParamName ':')? ParamValue
ParamName          ::= [A-Za-z0-9_-]+
ParamValue         ::= TripleQuoted | DoubleQuoted | SingleQuoted
                     | BracketQuoted | Unquoted
TripleQuoted       ::= '"""' .* '"""'
DoubleQuoted       ::= '"' [^"]* '"'
SingleQuoted       ::= "'" [^']* "'"
BracketQuoted      ::= '[[' ( [^\]] | ']'(?!']') )* ']]'
Unquoted           ::= ( '>'^('>') | [^\s>"'] )+

(* === Macro Definition (pragma) === *)
MacroDef           ::= '\define' SP MacroName '(' ParamList? ')'
                       ( SP? EOL Body '\end' MacroName?
                       | SP SingleLineBody EOL )
ParamList          ::= ParamDecl (',' ParamDecl)*
ParamDecl          ::= ParamName (':' DefaultValue)?
DefaultValue       ::= TripleQuoted | DoubleQuoted | SingleQuoted
                     | BracketQuoted | UnquotedDefault

(* === MVV Display (inline only) === *)
MVVDisplay         ::= MVVVariable | MVVFilter
MVVVariable        ::= '((' VarName ('||' Separator)? '))'
MVVFilter          ::= '(((' FilterExpr ('||' Separator)? ')))'
VarName            ::= [^()|]+?
Separator          ::= [^)]*
FilterExpr         ::= [\s\S]+?

(* === Block vs Inline === *)
(* Block form: the construct must be alone on its line,
   followed by EOL or end of input.
   Inline form: appears within a text run.
   MVV display is inline only. *)
```
